{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945082401/0989.xml":{"full_text":"Health Insurance Bill\nLifts Fear of Illness\nEDITORS NOTE: The author of this article, Dr. Boas, is Ass\u2019t\nClinical Professor of Medicine, College of Physicians and Sur\ngeons, Columbia University. He is the author of five books on\nmedical subjects, an authority on chronic diseases, and a mem\nber of the American Medical Ass\u2019n. He is chairman of the Phy\nsicians Forum.\nThe new Wagner-Murray Dingell Bill, S.1050, is the\nmeans of obtaining the right to medical care and the oppor\ntunity to achieve and enjoy good health for the people of\nour country. This bill, an amendment to the present Social\nSecurity Law, not only extends the coverage of social in\nsurance to about 15.000,000\npeople not now covered, but\nincludes many other forms\nof insurance which increase the\nsecurity and prosperity of all\nthe people, It provides for (1)\nretirement survivors and ex\ntended disability insurance (2)\nmedical care and hospitalization\ninsurance (3) unemployment in\nsurance and (4) temporary dis\nability insurance.\nWorking people have always\nfeared and dreaded illness and\nthis is natural because medical\ncare is not free it costs money\nand good medical care is ex\npensive. That is why so many\npeople do not get adequate\ncare. And when a can is sick\nthat is the very time when he\nis least able to pay for medical\ncare that is the time when\nwages stop and the bills pile up.\nFour Per Cent Contributions\nTo pay for all these forms of\nsecurity, the bill provides for\ninsurance contributions of four\nper cent each from employers\nand employees on all wages up\nto $3600 a year. The Federal\nGovernment will also supply\nadditional funds if they are re\nquired. (Self-employed persons\nwill contribute on a different\nbasis.)\nThe section of this bill which\nis of great interest to doctors is\nthe section dealing with medical\ncare and hospitalization insur\nance.\nAl! efforts to solve this prob\nlem have resulted so far in\nmakeshift voluntary plans which\nare expensive and do not pro\nvide complete coverage, or in\nindustrial insurance plans which\nusually do not cover the work\ner\u2019s wife or children. For this\nreason all the voluntary insur\nance plans now operating in this\ncountry have merely scratched\nthe surface of the workers\u2019\nneeds. Even the hospital insur\nance plans, which are not so\nexpensive, have only reached\nabout 12% of the population\nafter 12 years of operation.\nA system of sickness and hos\npital insurance which is avail\nable to practically the entire\npopulation at a price which it\ncan pay Is provided by the\nWagner Murray-Dingell bill. The\ncost of this insurance will re\nquire contributions of 1\u20194 of\nthe worker\u2019s pay on wages up\nto $3600 a year. (This is in\neluded in the 4% mentioned\nabove.) This means that for a\nMAXIMUM contribution of\n$54 00 a year (On an annual\nwage of $3600) the worker AND\nhis family would be entitled to\ncomplete medical care, the best\nmedical care, preventive and\ncurative, It would include ail\nthe services usually given by\ngeneral practitioners, plug all\nnecessary laboratory work, plus\nall the services rendered by\nspecialists when needed and it\nwouldn\u2019t matte\u00ae whether the\nservices were rendered in the\ndoctor\u2019s office or in the pa\ntient\u2019s home or on a hospital.\nIt would also include dental and\nhome nursing benefits.\nPay In Proportion\nNaturally, those who earn\nless would pay less in propor\ntian to income, but all would\nget the same amount and qual\nity of benefit^ regardless of\ntheir level of income.\nFor the first time, the people\nof America could feel secure in\nthe face of illness. No doctor's\nbills to pay. No putting off\nmedical care for fear of ex\npense. No wishing you could af\nford the X-rays the doctor says\nyou should have, nor that visit\nto a specialist when you need\none. No worry about how to\nmeet the expense of your wife\u2019s\nconfinement nor the medical\ncare of the baby after it has ar\nrived. No worry either, about\nthe Government dictating to\nyou which doctor you can go to,\nbecause you can choose your\nown. No more sitting on a clinic\nbench for hours waiting for the\ncharity of a hand-out of medical\ncare.\nWe know that this sounds\ngood to you. So does it to the\ndoctors in the Physicians Forum\n(national office of 510 Madison\nAvenue, New York 22, N. Y.)\nwhich is made up of forward\nthinking physicians throughout\nthe country who have long been\naware that a large part of our\npopulation does not get ade\nquate medical care because they\ncannot afford it. They know,\ntoo, that the doctors of this\ncountry also stand to benefit by\nthe health insurance provisions\nof the bill, for they will be as\nsured a regular income from\ntheir practice which many have\nnot enjoyed in the past.\nThe Physicians Forum is plan\nning a very active campaign to\nsecure passage of the Wagner\nMurray-Dingell bill and will do\nits utmost to cooperate with all\ninterested groups. They have\nalready prepared the first of a\nseries of popular pamphlets en\ntitled \u201cFor the People's Health,\u201d\nwhich will be available to all\norganizations interseted in the\npassage of this bill. Pamphlet\nPress, a division of Reynal and\nHitchcock, prepared this pam\nphlet and it was illustrated by\nCrocket Johnson well-known ar\ntist who draw* the Barnaby\ncomic strip.\nThe major responsibility for\nthe passage of the bill will fall\non the shoulders of organized\nlabor. Through its unions, la\nbor can make its demands\nknown to congress, to employ\ners, to other consumer groups,\nand yes! even to doctors, in\ncluding the American Medical\nAssociation.\nThe need to pass the Wagner\nMurray-Dingell Bill is more\nurgent now than ever, for we\narc facing the readjustments of\nthe postwar reconversion period.\nTo quote from President Tru\nman in his message to Congress\non May 28, 1945:\n\u201cEven if reconversion pro\nceed! rapidly, no amount of\nplanning makes jobs immedi\nately available for all displaced\npersonnel. We must provide\nmaximum security to those who\nhave given so fully of them\nselves on the fighting and pro\nduction fronts.\n\u201cThe transition from war to\npeace is part and parcel of the\nwar and we cannot shirk our\nobligation to those temporarily\nunemployed through no fault\nof their own.\u201d\nThe Wagner-Murray-Dingell\nBill is one of the important\nmeans by which we can hope to\nease the transition to peacetime\njobs and health aecurity for\nAmerican workers.\nPay Is Key To\nTeacher Problem\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014As nf\nFebruary 1, 1945, only 12,844\ndischarged veterans throughout\nthe country, in a total of 1,500,\n000 were attending schools un\nder the GI Bill of Rights. Among\namputees and neurosurgical\ncases\u2014\u201cthose who need it most\u201d\nonly about 2% indicate an in\nterest in serious \u201cbrain-build*\ning\u201d education, Stanley Frank,\nin a recent Saturday Evening\nPost, quotes Major Arthur\nGoodfriend, managing editor of\nStars and Stripes Paris edition,\non a possible cure: \u201cTho little\nred schoolhouse must change its\ntuuc.\u201d\n400.000 POW\nJobs Available\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\u2014Four\nhundred thousand German and\nItalian prisoners of war have\nbeen held in this country to\nwork on military, naval, indus\ntrial and agricultural projects,\naccording to Under Secretary\nof War Robert P. Patterson in\na statement here last week. He\nurged that all employers of\nPOWs make energetic efforts to\nreplace the prisoners with free\nAmerican workers who have\nbeen disemployed because of\nV-J cutbacks.\nTOPS for QUALITY\nPolitical\nAction\nby\nClayton\nRusch\nChairman\nof the Political Action Committee\nOPPORTUNITY\nIt has often been quoted\nthat opportunity knocks but\nonce. It is certainly true that\nwhen favorable circumstances\nfor the achievement of an ob\njective exists, the program\nshould be carried through be\nfore the situation changes.\nToday millions of workers\nface the immediate prospect\nof unemployment. This situa\ntion raises two questions. First\nis the disemployment of these\nworkers unavoidable, and sec\nond will the result be dis\nastrous to the national wel\nfare? The first answer is no,\nthe second is yes.\nInvoluntary unemployment,\neven for a temporary period\nduring reconversion, is not\nnecessary. Besides there is no\nassurance that reconversion\nalone will solve the employ\nment problem.\nPUBLIC WORKS\nThere is a real need for the\nimmediate establishment of\ngovernment sponsored public\nwork projects. These projects\ncan fill two important func\ntions. They can provide badly\nneeded facilities and services.\nThey can provide employment\nat living wages for all wage\nearners who are disemployed\nby the cancellation of war\ncontracts.\nThese projects should do\nwork which is the function of\ngovernment to provide, rather\nthan compete with private in\ndustry. As to the nature nf\nthe work, it should include\na program for rural electrifica\ntion, flood control, reforestra\ntion, soil conservation, erec\ntion of public buildings and\nparks construction of roads, an\nadequate housing program and\nall public enterprises which\ncontribute to the welfare of\nthe people.\nEmergency legislation is\nneeded at once to get this pro\ngram under way. As a result\nof war prices, taxes etc. the\nAmerican workers are not in\na financial position which\nwould enable them to wait for\na long period while a perma\nnent full employment program\nis being worked out.\nDO IT NOW\nEveryone should take the\ntime and trouble to sit. down,\nright now, and write their rep\nresentatives in Congress urg\ning that they do all in their\npower to assure the establish\nment nf Jobs For All im\nmediately. Address your let\nters to President Truman, U.\nS. Senators\u2014Robert Taft and\nHarold Burton and to Rep\nresentatives Homer Ramey\nand George Bender, Washing\nton, C.\nLetters to legislators will In\nfluence their decisions because\nthey want to be reelected and\nare therefore concerned about\nwhat the voters want. Of even\ngreater importance is the need\nto elect liberal, progressive\npeople at election time. In or\nder to vote you must be regis\ntered. If you are not registered\ngo to 217 Superior St. and\nregister.\nMembership in PAC is only\none dollar per year. If you are\nnot a member, see the PAC\nrepresentative at your shop or\nlocal or come come to nur\noffice and join now. Then par\nticipate in our crusade to pro\nmote passage of social legis\nlation to assure jobs for all,\nadequate social security meas\nsures and freedom of expres\nsion for all the people.\nNix on Franco!\nPRINCETON. N, (LPA)\u2014\n\u201cThe American public doesn\u2019t\nlike General Franco any better\ntoday than seven years ago,\u201d\nsays a recent Galltip poll com\nparing present attitudes toward\nthe Spanish dictator with those\ncurrent during the Spanish Civil\nWar, When asked whether they\nwould like to see Spain made a\nmember of the United Nations,\nunder Franco\u2019s government,\n80% said \u201cno!\u201d\nTHE TOLEDO UNION JOURNAL\nKenneth Cole Dies,\nHonored By CIO\nContinued from Page 1\nregrets at the passing of the\nfirst full-time executive secre\ntary of the CIO Council who\nalso had the distinction of being\nthe first full time Council sec\nretary in the United States.\nServices were conducted by\nRev. Harold L. Davis with whom\nMr. Cole was associated for\nyears on the executive board of\nthe Old Newsboys Goodfellow\nAssociation. Mr. Davis paid\neloquent tribute to his friend\nand spoke of the great loss which\nhis death means to all who knew\nhim.\nUniformed members of the\nFlying Squadrons of Willys\nOverland, Mather Spring and\nNational Supply Units of Local\n12 filed past the bier following\nthe brief services and stood with\nbared heads while the coffin\nwas born from the mortuary to\nthe hearse.\nActive pallbearers were Mur\nrell Morris, James Coleman,\nMichael Smith, Clarence Fore\nman, James Cook, Lawrence\nDudley and Thomas usscll.\nBurial was in Forest Ceme\ntery.\nMr. Cole\u2019s death followed a\nsecond operation which he had\nundergone several weeks ago.\nHe was operated on slightly\nmore than one year ago and had\nrecovered sufficiently to return\nto his post with the UAW-CIO\nin Washington, where he was\nemployed a& a liaaon man for\nthe Union.\nAided Public Understanding\nAs executive secretary of the\nToledo Industrial Union Coun\ncil, Mr. Cole did much to bring\nabout a clearer understanding\nof the CIO to the citizens of To\nledo. When the war came, he\nwas granted a leave of absence\nto take up duties in Washing\nton. Each year he has been re\nelected and his leave extended\nuntil the end of the war when it\nwas hoped he would return to\nhis former position as Council\nsecretary.\nMr. Cole had been in poor\nhealth for the past two years,\nbut he stuck to his Washington\npost until he collapsed just prior\nUnemployment compensation\nwill fill the gap between war\njobs and peace jobs on an in\ncreasing scale until that time\nafter V-J Day when reconver\nsion has been completed. The un\nemployment compensation pro\ngram is uniquely fitted for this\nrole\u2014it is designed to provide a\npartial income for covered work\ners during periods oL temporary\nunemployment.\nFor many workers, the filing\nof a claim for unemployment\ncompensation will be a new ex\nperience. Their knowledge of\nthe procedure for filing, at the\nbest, is of a general nature only\nthey know nothing, with rare\nexception, of how a claim is pro\ncessed by the Bureau and the\nbenefit checks finally mailed.\nThis illustrated article is in\ntended to aid public understand\ning of the procedi re followed in\nthe filing and processing of the\nordinary, regular claim for bene\nfits.\nStep No. 1\u2014When a worker\nbecomes unemployed and is un\nable to find another job, he\nshould go to his nearest local\noffice of the Ohio Bureau of Un\nemployment Compensatio or\nUnited States Employment Serv\nice and file a claim for unem\nployment compensation. Here he\nwill be:\nInterviewed by a claims-taker\nand asked, amon^ other things,\nto give his name, address, Social\nSecurity number, name of most\nrecent employer, and cause for\nunemployment.\nThis information is entered on\na form known as \u201d401\", which is\nsimply an application to deter\nmine benefits rights The \"401\u201d\nis sent to the Central Office of\nthe BUC at Columbus, where the\nclaim will be processed.\nThe claimant is given an iden\ntification card, known as the\nto his operation. He was sent to\nFord Hospital by plane and op\nerated on there in the hope of\nsaving his life.\nCIO leaders were unanimous\nin their praise for Mr. Cole. He\nmade many friends during the\nyears he was active in the Union\nand all who knew him paid high\ntribute to his qualities of heart\nand mind.\nHe first became interested in\nthe union movement when he\njoined a Willys-Overland picket\nline in 1919. He was a member\nof the CIO from its beginning\nand served as a shop committee\nman in the Chevrolet Unit of\nLocal 14, UAW-CIO. He held\nseveral offices in his own Local\nbefore entering upon his work\nas Council secretary.\nMr. Cole was a product of To\nledo and was educated in Toledo\nschools. He took up engineering\nstudies at the University of De\ntroit and worked in that city for\na time. While Mr. Cole had op\nportunities in factory supervi\nsion, he cast his lot with labor\nand was a vigorous worker i&t\nthe Union at all times.\nSurviving Mr. Cole are his\nwife and two children by a pre\nvious marriage, Kenalene, 19,\nand Kenneth, 12.\nHonorary pallbearers were\nRichard Gosser, regional UAW\ndirector Edward Cheyfitz,\nchairman Die Casters Lawrence\nSteinberg, Ohio URWDSEA di\nrector Melvin Schultz, president\nLocal 12, UAW Tom Burke, ex\necutive secretary TIUC O. J.\nPecord, managing editor TO\nLEDO UNION JOURNAL: Dan\nSahadi, recording secretary\nTIUC Chester Kapela, ACWA\nWilliam Akos, president Flat\nGlass Workers Scott Bebb, pres\nident Die Casters William Kloc\nkowski, Construction Workers\nIrving Woodtke, vice-president\nToledo Joint Council Ivo Erwin,\npresident Toledo Joint Council.\nCarl Wagner, president Local\n16, UAW August Scholle, Mich\nigan CIO director Frank Lich\nter, president Local 48, UAW\nEdward Lamb, labor attorney\nAlfred Davis, president Local\n11, UAW Norton Ackerman,\nCIO Canners and Agricultural\nWorkers, and Victor Reuther,\nUAW War Policy Division.\nInformation For\nThe Unemployed\nEditor\u2019s Note The following information is taken from the\nofficial publication for the Ohio Bureau of\nUnemployment Compensation. The steps to be followed will\nbe printed in succeeding issues. Most important of all is that\nyou visit your Local Union for information before filing your\nclaim. Local 12 has established a special office for this informa\ntion in Parlor \u201cI\u201d, 4th floor, 425 Winthrop St. It will be to your\ninterest to follow these instructions after consulting with your\nUnion first.\n\u201c450\u201d form, which also contains\nhis assigned weekly reporting\nday at the local office, with\nspaces for noting the days on\nwhich he reports. He must re\nport on the day assigned so long\nas he claims benefits.\nStep No. J\u2014 A basic require\nment for eligibility to unem\nployment compensation is that\nthe claimant be able to work\nand available for work in his\nusual occupation. As evidence\nof his availability he must regis\nter for work with, the United\nStates Employment Service at\nthe time of filing his claim and\nreport regularly thereafter as in-\nIf the employment service has\njob order for which the claim\nint is reosonably fitted, he will\nie referred to that employer.\nMeanwhile, after the work\ncgistration is completed, form\n\u2018401\u2019\u2019 containing information\n.bout the claim is sent on its\nvay to the Central Office of the\nlureau at Columbus. Here the\nprocessing of the claim start.\nContinued Next Week\nCoupon Clippers Gained\nNEW YORK (LPA)\u2014\u201cPheno\nmenal'' gains were made in\nstocks and bonds during the 44\nmonths and 7 days (Dec. 8, 1941\n:o Aug. 14, 1945) of the war,\niccording to a survey of Wall\nstreet dealings made by the As\nsociated Press. Many industrials,\n\u2022ails and utilities doubled and\njuintupled their prewar values,\nind \"many roads long in bank\nruptcy\" came out of the war\n\u2018with strengthened debt struc\nures.\u201d The Seaboard Railway,\n\u2019or instance, at the beginning of\nhe war sold \u201cstamped 4s\u2019\u2019 as\n510 now they bring $109. Amer\ncan labor produced this wealth\nhe coupon clippers get it.\nAn Ed'torial\nContinued from Page 1\nhave the ability and the imagination to meet the naw\nchallenge and come through to another victory.\nWe not only view the past 10 years with the satis\nfaction of conscious achievement but we welcome the fu\nture with a confidence born of victory over the difficulties\nof the past. With faces set to the days ahead, we shall\nmarch forward in unity to the struggles which we realize\nmust take place before we attain the goal which we have\nset for ourselves\u2014security for all*\nLabor-Employer\nGroup Ask\nLegislative Call\nContinued from Page 1\n000 purchasing power in this ci\nty every week. This increased\npurchasing power would reflect\nitself in increased business for\nthe corner druggist, grocer, meat\nmarket, hardware and other\nbusiness.\nIndustry and public members\nof the committee expressed\nthemselves as being favorable to\nthe proposal, but a 24 hour de\nferment was requested due to\nthe absence of several members\nof the committee. Wednesday\u2019s\nunanimous adoption of the pro\nposal followed.\nFollowing the meeting, Vice\nMayor Michael V. DiSalle called\nthe governor and informed him\nof the committee\u2019? action and\ntold him he would send him a\nletter relative to the recommen\ndation. Mr. DiSalle said that the\nGovernor wag very interested,\nparticularly in view of manage\nment\u2019s participation.\nFurther strength was added to\nthe request for immediate action\non the unemployment compensa\ntion act when the Manufacturer's\nDivision of the Chamber of Com\nmerce announced its endorse\nment of the action taken by the\nlabor-management committee.\nPresent unemployment com\npensation is set at $16 for 18\nweeks. The new act effective\nOct. 12 increases the benefits to\n$21 for 22 weexs.\nReconversion\nGets Top Spot\nIn Priority\nContinued from Page 1\nup its prerogative of deciding\nwage cases except where price\nincreases are necessitated. Col\nlective barganing is back, only\nfew unions are in a position to\nimmediately avail themselves of\nthe opportunity to reopen their\ncontracts as they apply to wages.\nStrikes Are Down\nOne of the results of the sur\nrender of the Japs is an almost\ncomplete cessation of strikes.\nLabor leaders say that unem\nployed workers do not strike. It\nis predicted here that strikes\nwill remain at a minimum for\nseveral months.\nWashington labor leaders are\nlooking forward to the return of\nCongress September -5 and are\nindignant over reports that the\nrecovening of the legislative\nbody may be deferred in order\nto give congressmen an oppor\ntunity to formulate legislation\nbearing upon the present situa\ntion.\nAwaiting congressional action\nis the bill advocated by Presi\ndent Truman increasing unem\nployment compensation to $25\nfor 26 weeks and the full em\nployment bill advocated by all\nlabor groups. Prompt action on\nthese bills will be a presidential\nmust to congress when it recon\nvenes.\nA y\nFriday, August 24, 1945\nBurke Promises\nLarge Labor\nDay Turnout\nContinued from Page 1\ntorney Edward Lamb and Judge\nStanley Grzezinski. They will\nreview the parade from the\nCommodore Perry Hotel.\nA basket picnic will be held\nin the afternoon at Walbridge\nPark which all CIO members are\nurged to attend. Races, ball\nthrowing, a tug of war and other\ncompetitive contests will feature\nthe afternoon with a plentiful\nsupply of cash prizes to the win\nners.\nEfforts are being made to\nsecure either Victor Reuther,\nDirector of the UAW-CIO War\nPolicy Division, or James Carey,\nsecretary-treasurer of the CIO\nto make the Labor Day address\nA special invitation to all CIO\nmembers has been sent by of\nficials of the Toledo Tomorrow\nexhibit showing in the Stratford\nTheater at the park. Labor is\ninterested in this plan for its\nmeans a better city with elimina\ntion of slums and a cleaner more\nlivable community.\nAdditional information rela\ntive to the Labor Day celebra\ntion will be announced next\nweek in the TOLEDO UNION\nJOURNAL. In the meantime,\nevery Local is making prepara\ntions for a large turnout for both\nthe parade and picnic.\nsays\nReddy Kilowatt\nyour Electric Servant\nYes, Reddy is always at home\nbehind every electric outlet,\nevery electric switch ready\nto spring into action at all\nhours of the day and\nnight...And Reddy is\nhome in doing all sorts\nof jobs,\\n business and indus\ntry, in th^ homes of our com\nmunity, an out on the farm,\nwhere bis help is so important\nthese days in making up for\nShortage of farm h0lp and thus\naiding tn vital food produc\ntion. Rely on Reddy, who has\nJcept on plugging during all\nthese war years\u2014and is\\still\nworking for you faithfully\\at\nhis Ipw pre-war wage.","height":"27054","width":"20586"}}
